tes symbolic refs like `refs/remotes/origin/<branchname>`\\n- **Two key functions read remote metadata:**\\n  - `/home/coder/git/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go:537` - `GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)` tries local branch first\\n  - `/home/coder/git/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go:722` - `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree(repo)` reads from remote-tracking refs\\n\\n**Example from common.go:**\\n```go\\nfunc GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree(repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n\\trefName := plumbing.NewRemoteReferenceName(\\\"origin\\\", paths.MetadataBranchName)\\n\\tref, err := repo.Reference(refName, true)  // Reads refs/remotes/origin/entire/checkpoints/v1\\n\\t// ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Note:** The codebase never instantiates a `Remote` object from go-git. It only reads remote-tracking references that were already created by git fetch operations.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. **How the Codebase Handles Auth for Remote Operations**\\n\\n**Critical Finding:** The codebase **does NOT use go-git's built-in auth mechanisms** (`transport.AuthMethod`, `http.BasicAuth`, `ssh.PublicKeys`, etc.). Instead:\\n\\n**ALL remote operations use the git CLI**, which delegates to:\\n- System SSH keys (for SSH URLs)\\n- Git credential helpers (for HTTPS URLs)\\n- User's own git configuration\\n\\n**Fetch Operations (git CLI):**\\n- `/home/coder/git/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/git_operations.go:315-355` - `FetchAndCheckoutRemoteBranch()`\\n- `/home/coder/git/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/git_operations.go:361-396` - `FetchMetadataBranch()`\\n- `/home/coder/git/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/push_common.go:134-144` - `fetchAndMergeSessionsCommon()`\\n\\n**Example:**\\n```go\\nfunc FetchAndCheckoutRemoteBranch(ctx context.Context, branchName string) error {\\n\\t// ... validation ...\\n\\t\\n\\t// Use git CLI for fetch (go-git's fetch can be tricky with auth)\\n\\trefSpec := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"+refs/heads/%s:refs/remotes/origin/%s\\\", branchName, branchName)\\n\\tfetch